reviews.title: They can get more out of the restaurant
reviews.text:
It's a restaurant in a quiet place.  We saw that the service was somewhat chaotic, so it was sometimes unclear if the tables had already been asked what they wished for. It could also be asked a little more regularly whether there is still enough to drink.
The food was adequate to taste, I had the Confit du Canard, unfortunately the fries were very weak.

reviews.title: Lunch Break
reviews.text: Popped in here when visiting Epernay. Lunch was reasonably good so easy to recommend especially when weather is good with the outside seating.

reviews.title: Not recommended
reviews.text:
Unfriendly staff, no flexibility, average to not satisfied food.
Not pleasant atmosphere, expensive in comparison to what we got

reviews.title: Nice eggs!
reviews.text: nice breakfast spot with friendly service! great fried eggs and strong coffee. great tea selection and well priced!

reviews.title: Lovely Crepe
reviews.text:
Lovely Crepes, with friendly service and the location is perfect. Away from the hustle and bustle of the road and in a quiet quad. 

We sat outside enjoying our food for quite a while and it was lovely to rest our feet after all that walking around the Champagne houses. I had a vegetarian crepe and my husband had a Caesar Crepe. Both were delicious and tasty.

The total bill with  a lemonade and water came to €32.20.

reviews.title: Slow service and food well below par
reviews.text:
Right in the centre of Epernay in a nice, quiet square, off the main road, this could be perfect.

My wife and I visited very recently on our annual visit to Epernay.  We were looking forward to the typical Bistro lunch that others in the town do so well.

We were sadly let down.  It took over 30 minutes to have our order taken, and when the food did arrive (a salad Nicoise with French trimmed beans is was awash with water and almost without flavour.  

The staff could not have shown less interest if they had tried - though the bill arrived as if by telepathy - that was impressive but little else was.

A few tweaks on service ethic and quality and it could be lovely.

reviews.title: Great late lunch!!
reviews.text:
You have to try one of the fabulous teas! 
The Darjeeling Warm duck salad was delicious. 
Friendly staff, clean welcoming and most enjoyable.

reviews.title: A very pleasant experience
reviews.text:
We visited Le Darjeeling a few times whilst staying at the ibis hotel that is nearby.
Service was always good and one waitress actually sorted out another table for us when someone started smoking next to us. That is one of the problems of dining outside. 
I preferred to have breakfast here in the morning because the service was much better than the hotel and we were always greeted with a smile.
They offer a wide range of tea and they have coffee from various countries.
This is a very popular place with French people.

reviews.title: Good For Lunch
reviews.text: We wanted something light for lunch and Le Darjeeling was ideal. There was a prix fixe menu, but I was able to choose just the starter from it - a small tuna tart. My companions all chose salads, which were good. It's also a good spot for ice creams or drinks in the afternoon.

reviews.title: Nice surprise
reviews.text:
Four of us there and having some crepes and salads and we were pleas fly surprised by what came in our plates and the freshness of the ingredients!
The service was straight to the point and with a smile for a reasonable price!
Not gastronomic but if you are after a quick bite in Eperney, this might really be a convenient place...

reviews.title: Very very average
reviews.text: Poor service, umpleasant atmosphere and rude owner. For somewhere where they advertise as being a great place for tea and coffee the coffee was incredibly bad. The breakfast we had was fairly ordinary and I wouldn't go back.

reviews.title: Quiet location
reviews.text: Had both lunch and dinner here on our stay in Epernay. Le Darjeeling is situated in a spacious square away from the traffic-noise which was a problem for most of the outdoor-restaurants in Epernay. Had  a three-course lunch;  paté, duck and cheese. With a glass of wine and a coffee afterwards I think it was around 25 euros per person. The food was good, service was ok, but nothing outstanding. But we liked it, so we went back for a salad another night. Salad was also good.

summaries.text: This restaurant is where France (the chef) meets Thailand (front of house). The result is fusion cuisine (pan-fried scallops, lentil salad with ginger, red curry shellfish bisque) with a few “unmissables” (“tom yum talay” soup, or wok-fried Dublin Bay prawns with panang curry…). Reasonable prices.

articleContent.title: Your go-to guide for dog-friendly travel

seoInfo.metaDescription: Traveling with your dog has never been easier—or more fun. Cities across the country boast pet-friendly hotels, parks, and activities. With CESAR® brand’s mission to make the world more pet-friendly and Tripadvisor’s top-rated spots, you can plan with confidence. Whether it’s a quick getaway or a bucket-list trip, our guides help you stay, play, and explore with your pup. Grab the leash and go!

tripContent.title: Discover a Fort Myers getaway for the whole family
tripContent.description: Planning a vacation the whole family will love can be tricky. Luckily, the islands, beaches and neighborhoods of Fort Myers have so much to offer kids of all ages. From water activities to wildlife interactions to family-friendly dining options, this memory-making itinerary has something for everyone.

seoInfo.metaDescription: Grab your crew and cozy sweaters—harvest season is in full swing

articleContent.title: Your family-friendly guide to Greenville, SC

seoInfo.metaDescription: Picnics, waterparks, museums, festivals, and plenty of unexpected all-ages activities—the equation for the perfect family getaway can be tough to balance. But there’s one place that does just this, promising plenty of memories to pack along with the souvenirs. Greenville, South Carolina checks all of the boxes, from hotels with plenty of family-friendly amenities to museums with interactive exhibits that’ll hold everyone’s attention (even a rambunctious toddler). Those in charge of packing can breathe easy: the weather is great year-round—the hottest month is July with temps up to 89 degrees, and the coolest is January, when the high hits around 55 degrees.

articleContent.title: How one family with autism tackles holiday trips

seoInfo.metaDescription: Writer Tiffany Hammond, a self-described "Autism mama," shares how her family preps for the busiest travel season of the year.

articleContent.title: A perfect day in the Grand Canyon

seoInfo.metaDescription: As a West Coast native, I’ve been visiting the Grand Canyon since I was little, and now I’m taking my own kids. It’s hard to pass up the chance to see billions of years of history in the layers of rock as you descend into the gorge, even if it’s just for a day. The best views are at sunrise and sunset, so that’s where I’ve started and ended this one-day itinerary.
